Document.author: momjian
Document.document: pg_atoi() does range check on int4 data only if "HAS_LONG_LONG" is defined based on the assumption that strtol() would return ERANGE if a platform does not support 64-bit integers. In current PostgreSQL 6.5 (and 6.4.2) distribution, "HAS_LONG_LONG" is defined only if platform is "alpha". (See include/port/alpha.h) I think the int4 range check should apply to linux_alpha as well. (I have not tested yet but I guess this might be applicable to newer Linux/i386 distributions which includes new GCC which implements long int as 64-bit int.)

Document.author: tgl
Document.document: Allow bare column names to be subscripted as arrays. This creates a reduce/reduce conflict, which I resolved by changing the 'AexprConst -> Typename Sconst' rule to 'AexprConst -> SimpleTypename Sconst'. In other words, a subscripted type declaration can't be used in that syntax any longer. This seems a small price to pay for not having to qualify subscripted columns anymore. Other cleanups: rename res_target_list to update_target_list, and remove productions for variants that are not legal in an UPDATE target listSEMICOLON rename res_target_list2 to plain target_listSEMICOLON delete position_expr in favor of using b_expr in that productionSEMICOLON merge opt_indirection into attr nonterminal, since there are no places where an unsubscripted attr is wantedSEMICOLON fix typos in Param supportSEMICOLON change case_arg so that an arbitrary a_expr is allowed, not only a column name.

Document.author: tgl
Document.document: Rewrite parser's handling of INSERT ... SELECT so that processing of the SELECT part of the statement is just like a plain SELECT. All INSERT-specific processing happens after the SELECT parsing is done. This eliminates many problems, e.g. INSERT ... SELECT ... GROUP BY using the wrong column labels. Ensure that DEFAULT clauses are coerced to the target column type, whether or not stored clause produces the right type. Substantial cleanup of parser's array support.

Document.document: While I was running some tests in psql, trying to figure out how to change the query string to handle any length, I discovered that under certain conditions, psql will core dump when handling long strings. Thus, the patch. It was caused by a buffer overrun, probably not noticeable in a lot of cases, but pretty noticeable in mine. Problem was caused by the fact that the length check is only performed after the check for a SEMICOLON to get the end of the query and execute. Cheers... MikeA
